node.text:
This is my remembrance of the days leading up to the bin Laden raid, the day of the raid centered on the iconic Situation Room photograph, and the day after.⁣
⁣
Note that the most important people from this day are not pictured at all. Our country owes a debt of gratitude to Admiral Bill McRaven, the former Commander of Special Operations, and the members of SEAL Team Six that planned for and executed the mission. They are the real heroes of this day. It was a real honor to be at Fort Campbell a few days later when they presented President Obama with the American flag that flew aboard the helicopter.⁣
⁣
If you have more questions, please leave them in the comments section. I will try to answer the ones that I can. I will not be able to respond to questions about what was on the screen during the raid or what I might have overheard.⁣
⁣
Please stay safe, practice social distancing, and wear a mask when you’re out and about!⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

Two weeks ago, I had the chance to discuss some of my photographs with Michael Shaw and Cara Finnegan of Chatting the Pictures. The program is produced by the visual and media literacy organization, Reading the Pictures. Here is the last part of the program looking at presidential leadership in a health crisis. We discussed one of my contact sheets from President Reagan’s visit to the National Institute of Health. The appearance took place during the AIDS epidemic on July 23, 1987, and it featured Reagan holding a baby that had the virus. 
Follow @readingthepictures on Instagram.

I had the chance to discuss some of my photographs with Michael Shaw and Cara Finnegan of Chatting the Pictures. ⁣
⁣
Here is Part 2 of a 3-part program looking at presidential leadership in a health crisis. ⁣
⁣
In this photo, taken October 10, 2011, President Obama walks into a hospital room at Walter Reed National Military Medical Center in Bethesda, Md., where he presented a wounded warrior with a Purple Heart.⁣
⁣
The program is produced by the visual and media literacy non-profit, Reading the Pictures. ⁣
⁣
Follow @readingthepictures on Instagram.⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
Absolutely stunning to read the alarming accounts about the waning weeks of the Trump administration from the viewpoint of Gen. Mark Milley, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. According to a forthcoming book by Phil Rucker and Carol Leonnig (and confirmed by Susan Glasser of the New Yorker), Milley was shaken that the twice-impeached former president would try to stage a coup using the military to hold onto power after losing the election.⁣
⁣
For perspective: during the Obama administration, the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs (the top military advisor to the President) was in every meeting that involved the military. ⁣
⁣
In addition, each year the President would meet, and have dinner with, the “combatant commanders”–top military leaders stationed around the globe. ⁣
⁣
Gen. Milley, who became Chairman in 2019, can be seen in the left-hand side of the second photo during the commanders meeting in 2016 when he was the Chief of Staff of the U.S. Army. (So at least Gen. Milley had the chance to observe a sane President before taking over the top job.)⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
The Los Angeles Dodgers–last year’s World Series champions–visited the White House today.⁣
⁣
Which reminded me of the last time the Dodgers won the World Series and visited the White House in 1988. I was prepared to do a group photo of the entire team and staff with President Reagan in the Oval Office. I had set up a ten foot ladder in advance (I find it amusing in retrospect that I thought to do a selfie). In any case, even with the ladder I was struggling to include everyone in the picture and kept asking the guys on the sides to squeeze in. I remarked that I still couldn’t see everybody in the picture. President Reagan quipped, “Pete, just take a step back,” while I was on the top step of the ladder.⁣
⁣
Another interesting change that occurred during my two stints at the White House 20+ years apart: when the World Series, Super Bowl, or NBA champions won, the team would inevitably come to the White House one or two days after the championship. Now the protocol has become that the team visits the following year usually when they have a game scheduled in Washington or Baltimore.⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
RIP, Donald Rumsfeld.⁣
⁣
The much maligned Secretary of Defense during the Bush 43 administration died today at 88.⁣
⁣
I offer this so hopefully some people pause before commenting: my job throughout my career both when I worked as a photojournalist and when I worked as a White House photographer was to make the best pictures I could no matter whom I was photographing. This was the case when I photographed then Secretary Rumsfeld at a hearing before the Senate Armed Services committee on Capitol Hill in 2005.⁣
⁣
